%[text] # Pile-Up Distortion in SPAD dToF Systems
%[text] In time-correlated single photon counting (TCSPC), pile-up refers to a systematic distortion of the recorded arrival-time histogram when the probability of detecting more than one photon within an excitation cycle, or within the effective dead time of the detection chain, is no longer negligible. In the classic single-stop case, the acquisition electronics records only the first detected photon associated with each laser cycle. At high photon flux, early-arriving photons are therefore preferentially recorded, while later-arriving photons in the same cycle are increasingly missed, causing an artificial bias in the histogram shape.
%[text] A separate but related source of distortion is detector or electronics dead time. After an avalanche, a SPAD is insensitive for a short interval (the 'dead time'), and the timing electronics or TDC may also impose a dead time after a registered event. These inactive intervals reduce the total number of recorded detections and can also produce histogram shape distortion.
%[text] This example demonstrates classic single-stop pile-up which produces a visually clear distortion. The SPAD dead time is set to a negligibly small value so that the observed distortion is dominated by the single-stop acquisition constraint rather than detector dead-time carryover.
%%
%[text] ## Setup
%[text] Define a Gaussian laser pulse at 50 ns on top of a uniform ambient background. The TDC is configured as single-stop (`maxHitsPerCycle = 1`), meaning at most one photon is recorded per laser cycle. SPAD dead time is set to 1 ns (negligible relative to the 100 ns cycle) so it does not contribute to the distortion. We sweep the mean detected photon count from 0.1 to 20 photons per cycle.
params = defaultSPADParams();
params.nCycles = 500000;     
params.cycleTime = 100e-9;  % 100 ns cycle (10 MHz laser rep rate)

% Single-stop TDC: only the first photon per cycle is recorded.
% Dead times are zeroed so pile-up is purely from the single-stop constraint.
params.spadDeadTime = 0;
params.tdcDeadTime = 0;
params.maxHitsPerCycle = 1;

% Disable all secondary effects to isolate pile-up distortion
params.trapProb = 0;
params.spadJitterFWHM = 0;
params.tdcJitterFWHM = 0;
params.dcr = 0;
params.pde = 1.0;

% Build time axis and ungated detection window
nBins = round(params.cycleTime / params.binWidth);
binCenters = ((0:nBins-1) + 0.5) * params.binWidth;
gateVector = ones(1, nBins);    

% Define a narrow Gaussian laser pulse centered at 50 ns
pulseCenter = 50e-9;
pulseSigma = 2e-9;                 % ~4.7 ns FWHM
pulse = exp(-0.5 * ((binCenters - pulseCenter) / pulseSigma).^2);

% Sweep mean detected photons/cycle from negligible to severe pile-up
meanDetPerCycle = [0.1, 1, 5, 20];
%%
%[text] ## Run Simulations
%[text] Sweep the mean detected photons per cycle, keeping signal-to-background ratio fixed at 1. At low flux ($\\mu = 0.1$) most cycles have no more than 1 photon arrival, so the histogram is undistorted. At high flux ($\\mu = 20$) nearly every cycle fires on the earliest arriving photon, so the histogram becomes dominated by early time bins.
nCases = numel(meanDetPerCycle);
allCounts = zeros(nCases, nBins);
detectionProbs = zeros(nCases, 1);

% Compute normalization integrals for splitting flux 50/50 signal vs background
sigIntegral = sum(pulse) * params.binWidth;
bgIntegral = params.cycleTime;

for si = 1:nCases
    % Split total flux equally between signal pulse and uniform background
    sigRate = (meanDetPerCycle(si) * 0.5) / sigIntegral;
    bgRate = (meanDetPerCycle(si) * 0.5) / bgIntegral;
    rateVector = reshape(sigRate * pulse + bgRate, 1, 1, []);

    params.seed = 42;  % Fixed seed for reproducibility
    result = runSPADSimulation(rateVector, gateVector, params);

    [counts, ~, histCenters] = buildHistogram(result, params);
    allCounts(si, :) = counts;

    % Detection probability: fraction of cycles that recorded a photon
    detectionProbs(si) = numel(result{1,1}.timestamps) / params.nCycles;
end
%%
%[text] ## Histogram Comparison
%[text] At low rates the histogram faithfully reproduces a Gaussian pulse on a flat background. As rate increases, pile-up creates a clear exponential decay — early bins consume the single detection slot, starving later bins of counts. The background after the pulse is almost completely suppressed at high flux. The dashed red line marks the true pulse center.
figure; %[output:24853ede]
tiledlayout(nCases, 1, TileSpacing="compact", Padding="compact") %[output:24853ede]
for si = 1:nCases
    nexttile %[output:24853ede]
    bar(histCenters * 1e9, allCounts(si, :), 1, ...
        FaceColor=[0.2 0.4 0.8], EdgeColor="none")
    hold on;
    xline(pulseCenter * 1e9, "r--", LineWidth=1.5);  % True pulse center
    xlim([0 params.cycleTime * 1e9]);
    ylabel("Counts");
    title(sprintf("\\mu = %.1f photons/cycle — P(det) = %.0f%%", ...
        meanDetPerCycle(si), detectionProbs(si) * 100))
    if si < nCases
        set(gca, XTickLabel=[]); 
    end
end
xlabel("Time (ns)") %[output:24853ede]
%%
%[text] ## Peak Shift and Background Asymmetry
%[text] Quantify pile-up two ways: (1) timing bias of the histogram peak relative to the true pulse center, and (2) the ratio of post-pulse to pre-pulse background counts. An undistorted histogram has zero peak shift and a ratio of 1.
peakPositions = zeros(nCases, 1); %[output:4296368c] %[output:69e0f1bb] %[output:42ce999e] %[output:5041a664]
bgRatios = zeros(nCases, 1);

% Define regions well outside the pulse (>4 sigma away) for background measurement
prePulseBins = histCenters < (pulseCenter - 8e-9);
postPulseBins = histCenters > (pulseCenter + 8e-9);

for si = 1:nCases
    h = allCounts(si, :);

    % Find histogram peak. Pile-up shifts this earlier than the true center
    [~, peakBin] = max(h);
    peakPositions(si) = histCenters(peakBin);

    % Ratio < 1 means post-pulse background is suppressed (photon starvation)
    preMean = mean(h(prePulseBins));
    postMean = mean(h(postPulseBins));
    bgRatios(si) = postMean / preMean;
end

% Convert peak shift to picoseconds for readability
peakShift = (peakPositions - pulseCenter) * 1e12;

figure; %[output:591da95c]
tiledlayout(1, 2) %[output:591da95c]

% Left panel: negative shift indicates peak pulled toward earlier times
nexttile %[output:591da95c]
semilogx(meanDetPerCycle, peakShift, "-o", LineWidth=2, MarkerSize=8) %[output:591da95c]
xlabel("Mean photons/cycle") %[output:591da95c]
ylabel("Peak shift (ps)") %[output:591da95c]
title("Timing Bias") %[output:591da95c]
grid on %[output:591da95c]

% Right panel: ratio of 1 = no distortion; lower = stronger pile-up
nexttile %[output:591da95c]
semilogx(meanDetPerCycle, bgRatios, "-s", LineWidth=2, MarkerSize=8, Color=[0.8 0.3 0.1]) %[output:591da95c]
yline(1, "k--", LineWidth=1);  % Ideal undistorted reference %[output:591da95c]
xlabel("Mean photons/cycle") %[output:591da95c]
ylabel("Post/Pre background ratio") %[output:591da95c]
title("Background Suppression") %[output:591da95c]
ylim([0 1.1]) %[output:591da95c]
grid on %[output:591da95c]

%%
%[text] ## Pile-Up Correction (Coates Method)
%[text] The Coates correction estimates true bin probabilities by compensating for the cumulative detection probability of earlier bins. For bin $i$, the corrected count is \\$\\hat{n}*i = N \\cdot n\_i / (N - \\sum*{j\<i} n\_j)$, where $N\\$ is the total number of cycles. This works well at moderate pile-up but saturates when early bins consume nearly all cycles.
correctedCounts = zeros(nCases, nBins);
for si = 1:nCases
    correctedCounts(si, :) = correctPileup(allCounts(si, :), params.nCycles);
end

% Build ideal (undistorted) reference histogram for comparison
refRate = (0.1 * 0.5) / sigIntegral;
refBg = (0.1 * 0.5) / bgIntegral;
idealShape = refRate * pulse + refBg;
idealShape = idealShape / sum(idealShape);  % Normalize to probability

figure; %[output:5895280c]
tiledlayout(nCases, 1, TileSpacing="compact", Padding="compact") %[output:5895280c]
for si = 1:nCases
    nexttile %[output:5895280c]

    % Normalize corrected histogram to probability for shape comparison
    corrNorm = correctedCounts(si, :) / sum(correctedCounts(si, :));
    rawNorm = allCounts(si, :) / sum(allCounts(si, :));

    plot(histCenters * 1e9, idealShape, "k--", LineWidth=1.5, ...
        DisplayName="Ideal (undistorted)")
    hold on
    plot(histCenters * 1e9, rawNorm, Color=[0.7 0.7 0.7], LineWidth=1, ...
        DisplayName="Raw (distorted)")
    plot(histCenters * 1e9, corrNorm, Color=[0.1 0.6 0.3], LineWidth=1.5, ...
        DisplayName="Coates corrected")
    xlim([0 params.cycleTime * 1e9])
    ylabel("Probability")
    title(sprintf("\\mu = %.1f photons/cycle", meanDetPerCycle(si)))
    if si == 1
        legend(Location="northeast")
    end
    if si < nCases
        set(gca, XTickLabel=[]);
    end
end
xlabel("Time (ns)") %[output:5895280c]

